\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 The case for it.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  The current spec has the front face as "cream diffuse + decal texture multiplied in" \'97 i.e., a clean illustration of the marks, rendered on top of imagined paper. That's a synthesis. What you're describing instead is "the actual scan IS the surface" \'97 which is consistent with the faithful-trace decision we just locked in last night. The SVG geometry is artifact-faithful (we don't clean up the gear teeth); putting the scan on the surface makes the 
\f5\i \strokec2 whole
\f0\i0 \strokec2  rendering artifact-faithful, not just the silhouette. The 1983 hand-drawn character \'97 Smith Rudolph's pen weight, the slight registration offsets, the paper texture from the print run \'97 survives into 3D. That's the "human feel" you're after, and you only get it by using the source pixels as the texture.\
It also collapses a previously-resolved product decision (illustrative vs. photographic, resolved as illustrative-first/photographic-in-M5) into a different third option that's strictly more interesting than either. So that resolution is now stale.\

\f2\b \strokec2 The case is also strengthened technically.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  Three.js doesn't care whether the front-face texture comes from a 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 CanvasTexture
\f0\fs24 \strokec2  (compositing vector decals) or an 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 ImageTexture
\f0\fs24 \strokec2  (the scan PNG) \'97 same code path, same UV mapping. And because the scan and your SVG vectors are already in registered coordinates (your 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 <use id="Background">
\f0\fs24 \strokec2  is at the same scale and origin as the paths you authored over it), the UVs basically write themselves: silhouette bounding box \uc0\u8594  corresponding region of the scan PNG. When the silhouette is partitioned along fold lines into hinged sub-meshes, each sub-mesh keeps the scan region that was on its flat-form face, and the texture "follows" the fold the same way the printed ink follows the paper when you actually crease it. That's the wrap you're describing, and it's free.\

\f2\b \strokec2 What changes downstream.
\f0\b0 \strokec2 \
The vector layers stop being for 
\f5\i \strokec2 rendering
\f0\i0 \strokec2 , but they don't disappear \'97 they shift to structure-only roles, which is fine: silhouette still defines extrusion; folds-valley/mountain still define hinge axes (and the existing fold-line overlay toggle becomes more useful, because it lets the reader see-through what the source page already shows); marks/axles still drive the connection graph and axle-alignment in JSON. The "Bake decals" step in \'a7SVG-to-3D-conversion gets simpler, not more complex.\
The reference-crop in the inspect panel is mostly redundant once the piece-in-3D already shows the scan. Could repurpose that slot to show the FULL plate with this piece highlighted, which is contextually richer.\

\f2\b \strokec2 Where I'd push back / flag concerns.
\f0\b0 \strokec2 \
Three real ones, in order of how much they'd affect the build:\
The first is 
\f2\b \strokec2 bundle size.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  Photographic textures cost more than vector decals. At native scan resolution (~600 DPI per the 2026-04-30 ruler measurement, ~2000\'963000 px on the long side per piece) \'d7 120 pieces, you'd ship hundreds of megabytes of texture if you weren't careful. The fix is straightforward \'97 downsample to viewer-appropriate resolution (256\'96512 px on the long side is plenty at the 1 m viewing distance the spec assumes) \'97 but it does mean the build pipeline needs a "downsample-for-viewer" stage that the current spec doesn't have. Probably ~50\'96100 KB per piece at viewer res, ~10 MB total bundle. That's fine for a static site, but worth knowing it's a real new pipeline step.\
The second is 
\f2\b \strokec2 back face vs. front face.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  The book only prints on one side; the back of the paper is just cream. So front face gets the scan, but back face stays cream/paper-color. The spec already says this; no change. Just pointing out we don't accidentally mirror the scan onto the inside of the folded box, which would look wrong.\
The third is 
\f2\b \strokec2 scan quality now matters for the final deliverable, not just for tracing.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  Right now, scan quality is a 
\f5\i \strokec2 means
\f0\i0 \strokec2  \'97 it has to be good enough to auto-trace. Under scan-as-texture, scan quality is also a 
\f5\i \strokec2 visible end
\f0\i0 \strokec2  \'97 every dust speck, glare, misalignment in the per-piece PNG is in the final 3D render. Flat-bed gen-2 scans are clean enough that this is mostly a non-issue, and "human feel" means we 
\f5\i \strokec2 want
\f0\i0 \strokec2  some of that \'97 but it raises the bar on captures we'd otherwise have shipped through tracing without thinking twice. Worth a re-look at the existing 117 captures in 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 source/pieces/
\f0\fs24 \strokec2  once we know they'll be the visible surface, not just trace input.\

\f2\b \strokec2 One thing I'm not sure about that I'd want to test before committing:
\f0\b0 \strokec2  how the scan texture reads under folding when the fold is sharp (paper-thin geometry, two scan regions meeting at a hard crease at e.g. 90\'b0). The mental model says "ink follows the paper around the fold" and that's right, but in a real-time 3D engine with mip-mapping and anti-aliasing, the very edge pixels of the fold region might look slightly off, especially at glancing angles. I don't expect this to be a real problem (paper-clock pieces are big enough, scans are clean enough) but I'd want to see piece 069 actually folded with its scan applied before I'd say "ship this." Which is what we're about to do anyway.\

\f2\b \strokec2 Net.
\f0\b0 \strokec2  I think this is a significant upgrade. It needs a spec revision (the "Bake decals" / "Material" sections in \'a7SVG-to-3D-conversion, the resolved aesthetic decision in \'a7Product decisions, and a new "downsample-for-viewer" stage in the asset pipeline), but the revision is in the direction of 
\f5\i \strokec2 fewer
\f0\i0 \strokec2  moving parts, not more. The held-spec-revision queue now has two items in it: layer model, and scan-as-texture. We can land both together when we come back to it.\
